{
  "doc_id": "59448",
  "text": "Tumour growth induces marked changes in the oxidative metabolism of distant tumour-free tissues and organs of the host [CITATION_1] . These changes include an increase in the level of pro-oxidant compounds and a reduction in the activities of antioxidant enzymes in extra-tumoral tissues [CITATION_2] . A better understanding of the role of cytokines and tumour factors [CITATION_3] , in the molecular mechanisms of protein wasting in skeletal muscle is essential for the design of therapeutic strategies in the near future. The Walker-256 tumour has been extensively used as an experimental model to induce cachexia in rats [CITATION_4] , but there have been no studies on whether the tumour and/or host cells produce a factor similar to PIF. In this study, we investigated the metabolic effects of 'Walker factor' (WF) purified from ascitic fluid from rats bearing the Walker 256 tumour, and its relationship to PIF.",
